79 /// The top declaration context.
80 class TranslationUnitDecl : public Decl,
81  public DeclContext,
82  public Redeclarable<TranslationUnitDecl> {
83  using redeclarable_base = Redeclarable<TranslationUnitDecl>;
84 
85  TranslationUnitDecl *getNextRedeclarationImpl() override {
86  return getNextRedeclaration();
87  }
88 
89  TranslationUnitDecl *getPreviousDeclImpl() override {
90  return getPreviousDecl();
91  }
92 
93  TranslationUnitDecl *getMostRecentDeclImpl() override {
94  return getMostRecentDecl();
95  }
96 
97  ASTContext &Ctx;
98 
99  /// The (most recently entered) anonymous namespace for this
100  /// translation unit, if one has been created.
101  NamespaceDecl *AnonymousNamespace = nullptr;
102 
103  explicit TranslationUnitDecl(ASTContext &ctx);
104 
105  virtual void anchor();
106 
107 public:
108  using redecl_range = redeclarable_base::redecl_range;
109  using redecl_iterator = redeclarable_base::redecl_iterator;
110 
111  using redeclarable_base::getMostRecentDecl;
112  using redeclarable_base::getPreviousDecl;
113  using redeclarable_base::isFirstDecl;
114  using redeclarable_base::redecls;
115  using redeclarable_base::redecls_begin;
116  using redeclarable_base::redecls_end;
117 
118  ASTContext &getASTContext() const { return Ctx; }
119 
120  NamespaceDecl *getAnonymousNamespace() const { return AnonymousNamespace; }
121  void setAnonymousNamespace(NamespaceDecl *D) { AnonymousNamespace = D; }
122 
123  static TranslationUnitDecl *Create(ASTContext &C);
124 
125  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
126  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
127  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == TranslationUnit; }
128  static DeclContext *castToDeclContext(const TranslationUnitDecl *D) {
129  return static_cast<DeclContext *>(const_cast<TranslationUnitDecl*>(D));
130  }
131  static TranslationUnitDecl *castFromDeclContext(const DeclContext *DC) {
132  return static_cast<TranslationUnitDecl *>(const_cast<DeclContext*>(DC));
133  }
134 };

203 /// Declaration context for names declared as extern "C" in C++. This
204 /// is neither the semantic nor lexical context for such declarations, but is
205 /// used to check for conflicts with other extern "C" declarations. Example:
206 ///
207 /// \code
208 /// namespace N { extern "C" void f(); } // #1
209 /// void N::f() {} // #2
210 /// namespace M { extern "C" void f(); } // #3
211 /// \endcode
212 ///
213 /// The semantic context of #1 is namespace N and its lexical context is the
214 /// LinkageSpecDecl; the semantic context of #2 is namespace N and its lexical
215 /// context is the TU. However, both declarations are also visible in the
216 /// extern "C" context.
217 ///
218 /// The declaration at #3 finds it is a redeclaration of \c N::f through
219 /// lookup in the extern "C" context.
220 class ExternCContextDecl : public Decl, public DeclContext {
221  explicit ExternCContextDecl(TranslationUnitDecl *TU)
222  : Decl(ExternCContext, TU, SourceLocation()),
223  DeclContext(ExternCContext) {}
224 
225  virtual void anchor();
226 
227 public:
228  static ExternCContextDecl *Create(const ASTContext &C,
229  TranslationUnitDecl *TU);
230 
231  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
232  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
233  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == ExternCContext; }
234  static DeclContext *castToDeclContext(const ExternCContextDecl *D) {
235  return static_cast<DeclContext *>(const_cast<ExternCContextDecl*>(D));
236  }
237  static ExternCContextDecl *castFromDeclContext(const DeclContext *DC) {
238  return static_cast<ExternCContextDecl *>(const_cast<DeclContext*>(DC));
239  }
240 };

242 /// This represents a decl that may have a name. Many decls have names such
243 /// as ObjCMethodDecl, but not \@class, etc.
244 ///
245 /// Note that not every NamedDecl is actually named (e.g., a struct might
246 /// be anonymous), and not every name is an identifier.
247 class NamedDecl : public Decl {
248  /// The name of this declaration, which is typically a normal
249  /// identifier but may also be a special kind of name (C++
250  /// constructor, Objective-C selector, etc.)
251  DeclarationName Name;
252 
253  virtual void anchor();
254 
255 private:
256  NamedDecl *getUnderlyingDeclImpl() LLVM_READONLY;
257 
258 protected:
259  NamedDecl(Kind DK, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation L, DeclarationName N)
260  : Decl(DK, DC, L), Name(N) {}
261 
262 public:
263  /// Get the identifier that names this declaration, if there is one.
264  ///
265  /// This will return NULL if this declaration has no name (e.g., for
266  /// an unnamed class) or if the name is a special name (C++ constructor,
267  /// Objective-C selector, etc.).
268  IdentifierInfo *getIdentifier() const { return Name.getAsIdentifierInfo(); }
269 
270  /// Get the name of identifier for this declaration as a StringRef.
271  ///
272  /// This requires that the declaration have a name and that it be a simple
273  /// identifier.
274  StringRef getName() const {
275  assert(Name.isIdentifier() && "Name is not a simple identifier");
276  return getIdentifier() ? getIdentifier()->getName() : "";
277  }
278 
279  /// Get a human-readable name for the declaration, even if it is one of the
280  /// special kinds of names (C++ constructor, Objective-C selector, etc).
281  ///
282  /// Creating this name requires expensive string manipulation, so it should
283  /// be called only when performance doesn't matter. For simple declarations,
284  /// getNameAsCString() should suffice.
285  //
286  // FIXME: This function should be renamed to indicate that it is not just an
287  // alternate form of getName(), and clients should move as appropriate.
288  //
289  // FIXME: Deprecated, move clients to getName().
290  std::string getNameAsString() const { return Name.getAsString(); }
291 
292  /// Pretty-print the unqualified name of this declaration. Can be overloaded
293  /// by derived classes to provide a more user-friendly name when appropriate.
294  virtual void printName(raw_ostream &os) const;
295 
296  /// Get the actual, stored name of the declaration, which may be a special
297  /// name.
298  ///
299  /// Note that generally in diagnostics, the non-null \p NamedDecl* itself
300  /// should be sent into the diagnostic instead of using the result of
301  /// \p getDeclName().
302  ///
303  /// A \p DeclarationName in a diagnostic will just be streamed to the output,
304  /// which will directly result in a call to \p DeclarationName::print.
305  ///
306  /// A \p NamedDecl* in a diagnostic will also ultimately result in a call to
307  /// \p DeclarationName::print, but with two customisation points along the
308  /// way (\p getNameForDiagnostic and \p printName). These are used to print
309  /// the template arguments if any, and to provide a user-friendly name for
310  /// some entities (such as unnamed variables and anonymous records).
311  DeclarationName getDeclName() const { return Name; }
312 
313  /// Set the name of this declaration.
314  void setDeclName(DeclarationName N) { Name = N; }
315 
316  /// Returns a human-readable qualified name for this declaration, like
317  /// A::B::i, for i being member of namespace A::B.
318  ///
319  /// If the declaration is not a member of context which can be named (record,
320  /// namespace), it will return the same result as printName().
321  ///
322  /// Creating this name is expensive, so it should be called only when
323  /// performance doesn't matter.
324  void printQualifiedName(raw_ostream &OS) const;
325  void printQualifiedName(raw_ostream &OS, const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
326  bool WithGlobalNsPrefix = false) const;
327 
328  /// Print only the nested name specifier part of a fully-qualified name,
329  /// including the '::' at the end. E.g.
330  /// when `printQualifiedName(D)` prints "A::B::i",
331  /// this function prints "A::B::".
332  void printNestedNameSpecifier(raw_ostream &OS) const;
333  void printNestedNameSpecifier(raw_ostream &OS, const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
334  bool WithGlobalNsPrefix = false) const;
335 
336  // FIXME: Remove string version.
337  std::string getQualifiedNameAsString(bool WithGlobalNsPrefix = false) const;
338 
339  /// Appends a human-readable name for this declaration into the given stream.
340  ///
341  /// This is the method invoked by Sema when displaying a NamedDecl
342  /// in a diagnostic. It does not necessarily produce the same
343  /// result as printName(); for example, class template
344  /// specializations are printed with their template arguments.
345  virtual void getNameForDiagnostic(raw_ostream &OS,
346  const PrintingPolicy &Policy,
347  bool Qualified) const;
348 
349  /// Determine whether this declaration, if known to be well-formed within
350  /// its context, will replace the declaration OldD if introduced into scope.
351  ///
352  /// A declaration will replace another declaration if, for example, it is
353  /// a redeclaration of the same variable or function, but not if it is a
354  /// declaration of a different kind (function vs. class) or an overloaded
355  /// function.
356  ///
357  /// \param IsKnownNewer \c true if this declaration is known to be newer
358  /// than \p OldD (for instance, if this declaration is newly-created).
359  bool declarationReplaces(NamedDecl *OldD, bool IsKnownNewer = true) const;
360 
361  /// Determine whether this declaration has linkage.
362  bool hasLinkage() const;
363 
364  using Decl::isModulePrivate;
365  using Decl::setModulePrivate;
366 
367  /// Determine whether this declaration is a C++ class member.
368  bool isCXXClassMember() const {
369  const DeclContext *DC = getDeclContext();
370 
371  // C++0x [class.mem]p1:
372  // The enumerators of an unscoped enumeration defined in
373  // the class are members of the class.
374  if (isa<EnumDecl>(DC))
375  DC = DC->getRedeclContext();
376 
377  return DC->isRecord();
378  }
379 
380  /// Determine whether the given declaration is an instance member of
381  /// a C++ class.
382  bool isCXXInstanceMember() const;
383 
384  /// Determine if the declaration obeys the reserved identifier rules of the
385  /// given language.
386  ReservedIdentifierStatus isReserved(const LangOptions &LangOpts) const;
387 
388  /// Determine what kind of linkage this entity has.
389  ///
390  /// This is not the linkage as defined by the standard or the codegen notion
391  /// of linkage. It is just an implementation detail that is used to compute
392  /// those.
393  Linkage getLinkageInternal() const;
394 
395  /// Get the linkage from a semantic point of view. Entities in
396  /// anonymous namespaces are external (in c++98).
397  Linkage getFormalLinkage() const {
398  return clang::getFormalLinkage(getLinkageInternal());
399  }
400 
401  /// True if this decl has external linkage.
402  bool hasExternalFormalLinkage() const {
403  return isExternalFormalLinkage(getLinkageInternal());
404  }
405 
406  bool isExternallyVisible() const {
407  return clang::isExternallyVisible(getLinkageInternal());
408  }
409 
410  /// Determine whether this declaration can be redeclared in a
411  /// different translation unit.
412  bool isExternallyDeclarable() const {
413  return isExternallyVisible() && !getOwningModuleForLinkage();
414  }
415 
416  /// Determines the visibility of this entity.
417  Visibility getVisibility() const {
418  return getLinkageAndVisibility().getVisibility();
419  }
420 
421  /// Determines the linkage and visibility of this entity.
422  LinkageInfo getLinkageAndVisibility() const;
423 
424  /// Kinds of explicit visibility.
425  enum ExplicitVisibilityKind {
426  /// Do an LV computation for, ultimately, a type.
427  /// Visibility may be restricted by type visibility settings and
428  /// the visibility of template arguments.
429  VisibilityForType,
430 
431  /// Do an LV computation for, ultimately, a non-type declaration.
432  /// Visibility may be restricted by value visibility settings and
433  /// the visibility of template arguments.
434  VisibilityForValue
435  };
436 
437  /// If visibility was explicitly specified for this
438  /// declaration, return that visibility.
439  Optional<Visibility>
440  getExplicitVisibility(ExplicitVisibilityKind kind) const;
441 
442  /// True if the computed linkage is valid. Used for consistency
443  /// checking. Should always return true.
444  bool isLinkageValid() const;
445 
446  /// True if something has required us to compute the linkage
447  /// of this declaration.
448  ///
449  /// Language features which can retroactively change linkage (like a
450  /// typedef name for linkage purposes) may need to consider this,
451  /// but hopefully only in transitory ways during parsing.
452  bool hasLinkageBeenComputed() const {
453  return hasCachedLinkage();
454  }
455 
456  /// Looks through UsingDecls and ObjCCompatibleAliasDecls for
457  /// the underlying named decl.
458  NamedDecl *getUnderlyingDecl() {
459  // Fast-path the common case.
460  if (this->getKind() != UsingShadow &&
461  this->getKind() != ConstructorUsingShadow &&
462  this->getKind() != ObjCCompatibleAlias &&
463  this->getKind() != NamespaceAlias)
464  return this;
465 
466  return getUnderlyingDeclImpl();
467  }
468  const NamedDecl *getUnderlyingDecl() const {
469  return const_cast<NamedDecl*>(this)->getUnderlyingDecl();
470  }
471 
472  NamedDecl *getMostRecentDecl() {
473  return cast<NamedDecl>(static_cast<Decl *>(this)->getMostRecentDecl());
474  }
475  const NamedDecl *getMostRecentDecl() const {
476  return const_cast<NamedDecl*>(this)->getMostRecentDecl();
477  }
478 
479  ObjCStringFormatFamily getObjCFStringFormattingFamily() const;
480 
481  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
482  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K >= firstNamed && K <= lastNamed; }
483 };
484 
485 inline raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const NamedDecl &ND) {
486  ND.printName(OS);
487  return OS;
488 }

490 /// Represents the declaration of a label. Labels also have a
491 /// corresponding LabelStmt, which indicates the position that the label was
492 /// defined at. For normal labels, the location of the decl is the same as the
493 /// location of the statement. For GNU local labels (__label__), the decl
494 /// location is where the __label__ is.
495 class LabelDecl : public NamedDecl {
496  LabelStmt *TheStmt;
497  StringRef MSAsmName;
498  bool MSAsmNameResolved = false;
499 
500  /// For normal labels, this is the same as the main declaration
501  /// label, i.e., the location of the identifier; for GNU local labels,
502  /// this is the location of the __label__ keyword.
503  SourceLocation LocStart;
504 
505  LabelDecl(DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation IdentL, IdentifierInfo *II,
506  LabelStmt *S, SourceLocation StartL)
507  : NamedDecl(Label, DC, IdentL, II), TheStmt(S), LocStart(StartL) {}
508 
509  void anchor() override;
510 
511 public:
512  static LabelDecl *Create(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
513  SourceLocation IdentL, IdentifierInfo *II);
514  static LabelDecl *Create(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
515  SourceLocation IdentL, IdentifierInfo *II,
516  SourceLocation GnuLabelL);
517  static LabelDecl *CreateDeserialized(ASTContext &C, unsigned ID);
518 
519  LabelStmt *getStmt() const { return TheStmt; }
520  void setStmt(LabelStmt *T) { TheStmt = T; }
521 
522  bool isGnuLocal() const { return LocStart != getLocation(); }
523  void setLocStart(SourceLocation L) { LocStart = L; }
524 
525  SourceRange getSourceRange() const override LLVM_READONLY {
526  return SourceRange(LocStart, getLocation());
527  }
528 
529  bool isMSAsmLabel() const { return !MSAsmName.empty(); }
530  bool isResolvedMSAsmLabel() const { return isMSAsmLabel() && MSAsmNameResolved; }
531  void setMSAsmLabel(StringRef Name);
532  StringRef getMSAsmLabel() const { return MSAsmName; }
533  void setMSAsmLabelResolved() { MSAsmNameResolved = true; }
534 
535  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
536  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
537  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == Label; }
538 };

540 /// Represent a C++ namespace.
541 class NamespaceDecl : public NamedDecl, public DeclContext,
542  public Redeclarable<NamespaceDecl>
543 {
544  /// The starting location of the source range, pointing
545  /// to either the namespace or the inline keyword.
546  SourceLocation LocStart;
547 
548  /// The ending location of the source range.
549  SourceLocation RBraceLoc;
550 
551  /// A pointer to either the anonymous namespace that lives just inside
552  /// this namespace or to the first namespace in the chain (the latter case
553  /// only when this is not the first in the chain), along with a
554  /// boolean value indicating whether this is an inline namespace.
555  llvm::PointerIntPair<NamespaceDecl *, 1, bool> AnonOrFirstNamespaceAndInline;
556 
557  NamespaceDecl(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC, bool Inline,
558  SourceLocation StartLoc, SourceLocation IdLoc,
559  IdentifierInfo *Id, NamespaceDecl *PrevDecl);
560 
561  using redeclarable_base = Redeclarable<NamespaceDecl>;
562 
563  NamespaceDecl *getNextRedeclarationImpl() override;
564  NamespaceDecl *getPreviousDeclImpl() override;
565  NamespaceDecl *getMostRecentDeclImpl() override;
566 
567 public:
568  friend class ASTDeclReader;
569  friend class ASTDeclWriter;
570 
571  static NamespaceDecl *Create(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
572  bool Inline, SourceLocation StartLoc,
573  SourceLocation IdLoc, IdentifierInfo *Id,
574  NamespaceDecl *PrevDecl);
575 
576  static NamespaceDecl *CreateDeserialized(ASTContext &C, unsigned ID);
577 
578  using redecl_range = redeclarable_base::redecl_range;
579  using redecl_iterator = redeclarable_base::redecl_iterator;
580 
581  using redeclarable_base::redecls_begin;
582  using redeclarable_base::redecls_end;
583  using redeclarable_base::redecls;
584  using redeclarable_base::getPreviousDecl;
585  using redeclarable_base::getMostRecentDecl;
586  using redeclarable_base::isFirstDecl;
587 
588  /// Returns true if this is an anonymous namespace declaration.
589  ///
590  /// For example:
591  /// \code
592  /// namespace {
593  /// ...
594  /// };
595  /// \endcode
596  /// q.v. C++ [namespace.unnamed]
597  bool isAnonymousNamespace() const {
598  return !getIdentifier();
599  }
600 
601  /// Returns true if this is an inline namespace declaration.
602  bool isInline() const {
603  return AnonOrFirstNamespaceAndInline.getInt();
604  }
605 
606  /// Set whether this is an inline namespace declaration.
607  void setInline(bool Inline) {
608  AnonOrFirstNamespaceAndInline.setInt(Inline);
609  }
610 
611  /// Returns true if the inline qualifier for \c Name is redundant.
612  bool isRedundantInlineQualifierFor(DeclarationName Name) const {
613  if (!isInline())
614  return false;
615  auto X = lookup(Name);
616  // We should not perform a lookup within a transparent context, so find a
617  // non-transparent parent context.
618  auto Y = getParent()->getNonTransparentContext()->lookup(Name);
619  return std::distance(X.begin(), X.end()) ==
620  std::distance(Y.begin(), Y.end());
621  }
622 
623  /// Get the original (first) namespace declaration.
624  NamespaceDecl *getOriginalNamespace();
625 
626  /// Get the original (first) namespace declaration.
627  const NamespaceDecl *getOriginalNamespace() const;
628 
629  /// Return true if this declaration is an original (first) declaration
630  /// of the namespace. This is false for non-original (subsequent) namespace
631  /// declarations and anonymous namespaces.
632  bool isOriginalNamespace() const;
633 
634  /// Retrieve the anonymous namespace nested inside this namespace,
635  /// if any.
636  NamespaceDecl *getAnonymousNamespace() const {
637  return getOriginalNamespace()->AnonOrFirstNamespaceAndInline.getPointer();
638  }
639 
640  void setAnonymousNamespace(NamespaceDecl *D) {
641  getOriginalNamespace()->AnonOrFirstNamespaceAndInline.setPointer(D);
642  }
643 
644  /// Retrieves the canonical declaration of this namespace.
645  NamespaceDecl *getCanonicalDecl() override {
646  return getOriginalNamespace();
647  }
648  const NamespaceDecl *getCanonicalDecl() const {
649  return getOriginalNamespace();
650  }
651 
652  SourceRange getSourceRange() const override LLVM_READONLY {
653  return SourceRange(LocStart, RBraceLoc);
654  }
655 
656  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return LocStart; }
657  SourceLocation getRBraceLoc() const { return RBraceLoc; }
658  void setLocStart(SourceLocation L) { LocStart = L; }
659  void setRBraceLoc(SourceLocation L) { RBraceLoc = L; }
660 
661  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
662  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
663  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == Namespace; }
664  static DeclContext *castToDeclContext(const NamespaceDecl *D) {
665  return static_cast<DeclContext *>(const_cast<NamespaceDecl*>(D));
666  }
667  static NamespaceDecl *castFromDeclContext(const DeclContext *DC) {
668  return static_cast<NamespaceDecl *>(const_cast<DeclContext*>(DC));
669  }
670 };

672 /// Represent the declaration of a variable (in which case it is
673 /// an lvalue) a function (in which case it is a function designator) or
674 /// an enum constant.
675 class ValueDecl : public NamedDecl {
676  QualType DeclType;
677 
678  void anchor() override;
679 
680 protected:
681  ValueDecl(Kind DK, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation L,
682  DeclarationName N, QualType T)
683  : NamedDecl(DK, DC, L, N), DeclType(T) {}
684 
685 public:
686  QualType getType() const { return DeclType; }
687  void setType(QualType newType) { DeclType = newType; }
688 
689  /// Determine whether this symbol is weakly-imported,
690  /// or declared with the weak or weak-ref attr.
691  bool isWeak() const;
692 
693  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
694  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
695  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K >= firstValue && K <= lastValue; }
696 };

698 /// A struct with extended info about a syntactic
699 /// name qualifier, to be used for the case of out-of-line declarations.
700 struct QualifierInfo {
701  NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc;
702 
703  /// The number of "outer" template parameter lists.
704  /// The count includes all of the template parameter lists that were matched
705  /// against the template-ids occurring into the NNS and possibly (in the
706  /// case of an explicit specialization) a final "template <>".
707  unsigned NumTemplParamLists = 0;
708 
709  /// A new-allocated array of size NumTemplParamLists,
710  /// containing pointers to the "outer" template parameter lists.
711  /// It includes all of the template parameter lists that were matched
712  /// against the template-ids occurring into the NNS and possibly (in the
713  /// case of an explicit specialization) a final "template <>".
714  TemplateParameterList** TemplParamLists = nullptr;
715 
716  QualifierInfo() = default;
717  QualifierInfo(const QualifierInfo &) = delete;
718  QualifierInfo& operator=(const QualifierInfo &) = delete;
719 
720  /// Sets info about "outer" template parameter lists.
721  void setTemplateParameterListsInfo(ASTContext &Context,
722  ArrayRef<TemplateParameterList *> TPLists);
723 };

725 /// Represents a ValueDecl that came out of a declarator.
726 /// Contains type source information through TypeSourceInfo.
727 class DeclaratorDecl : public ValueDecl {
728  // A struct representing a TInfo, a trailing requires-clause and a syntactic
729  // qualifier, to be used for the (uncommon) case of out-of-line declarations
730  // and constrained function decls.
731  struct ExtInfo : public QualifierInfo {
732  TypeSourceInfo *TInfo;
733  Expr *TrailingRequiresClause = nullptr;
734  };
735 
736  llvm::PointerUnion<TypeSourceInfo *, ExtInfo *> DeclInfo;
737 
738  /// The start of the source range for this declaration,
739  /// ignoring outer template declarations.
740  SourceLocation InnerLocStart;
741 
742  bool hasExtInfo() const { return DeclInfo.is<ExtInfo*>(); }
743  ExtInfo *getExtInfo() { return DeclInfo.get<ExtInfo*>(); }
744  const ExtInfo *getExtInfo() const { return DeclInfo.get<ExtInfo*>(); }
745 
746 protected:
747  DeclaratorDecl(Kind DK, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation L,
748  DeclarationName N, QualType T, TypeSourceInfo *TInfo,
749  SourceLocation StartL)
750  : ValueDecl(DK, DC, L, N, T), DeclInfo(TInfo), InnerLocStart(StartL) {}
751 
752 public:
753  friend class ASTDeclReader;
754  friend class ASTDeclWriter;
755 
756  TypeSourceInfo *getTypeSourceInfo() const {
757  return hasExtInfo()
758  ? getExtInfo()->TInfo
759  : DeclInfo.get<TypeSourceInfo*>();
760  }
761 
762  void setTypeSourceInfo(TypeSourceInfo *TI) {
763  if (hasExtInfo())
764  getExtInfo()->TInfo = TI;
765  else
766  DeclInfo = TI;
767  }
768 
769  /// Return start of source range ignoring outer template declarations.
770  SourceLocation getInnerLocStart() const { return InnerLocStart; }
771  void setInnerLocStart(SourceLocation L) { InnerLocStart = L; }
772 
773  /// Return start of source range taking into account any outer template
774  /// declarations.
775  SourceLocation getOuterLocStart() const;
776 
777  SourceRange getSourceRange() const override LLVM_READONLY;
778 
779  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
780  return getOuterLocStart();
781  }
782 
783  /// Retrieve the nested-name-specifier that qualifies the name of this
784  /// declaration, if it was present in the source.
785  NestedNameSpecifier *getQualifier() const {
786  return hasExtInfo() ? getExtInfo()->QualifierLoc.getNestedNameSpecifier()
787  : nullptr;
788  }
789 
790  /// Retrieve the nested-name-specifier (with source-location
791  /// information) that qualifies the name of this declaration, if it was
792  /// present in the source.
793  NestedNameSpecifierLoc getQualifierLoc() const {
794  return hasExtInfo() ? getExtInfo()->QualifierLoc
795  : NestedNameSpecifierLoc();
796  }
797 
798  void setQualifierInfo(NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc);
799 
800  /// \brief Get the constraint-expression introduced by the trailing
801  /// requires-clause in the function/member declaration, or null if no
802  /// requires-clause was provided.
803  Expr *getTrailingRequiresClause() {
804  return hasExtInfo() ? getExtInfo()->TrailingRequiresClause
805  : nullptr;
806  }
807 
808  const Expr *getTrailingRequiresClause() const {
809  return hasExtInfo() ? getExtInfo()->TrailingRequiresClause
810  : nullptr;
811  }
812 
813  void setTrailingRequiresClause(Expr *TrailingRequiresClause);
814 
815  unsigned getNumTemplateParameterLists() const {
816  return hasExtInfo() ? getExtInfo()->NumTemplParamLists : 0;
817  }
818 
819  TemplateParameterList *getTemplateParameterList(unsigned index) const {
820  assert(index < getNumTemplateParameterLists());
821  return getExtInfo()->TemplParamLists[index];
822  }
823 
824  void setTemplateParameterListsInfo(ASTContext &Context,
825  ArrayRef<TemplateParameterList *> TPLists);
826 
827  SourceLocation getTypeSpecStartLoc() const;
828  SourceLocation getTypeSpecEndLoc() const;
829 
830  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
831  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
832  static bool classofKind(Kind K) {
833  return K >= firstDeclarator && K <= lastDeclarator;
834  }
835 };
836 
837 /// Structure used to store a statement, the constant value to
838 /// which it was evaluated (if any), and whether or not the statement
839 /// is an integral constant expression (if known).
840 struct EvaluatedStmt {
841  /// Whether this statement was already evaluated.
842  bool WasEvaluated : 1;
843 
844  /// Whether this statement is being evaluated.
845  bool IsEvaluating : 1;
846 
847  /// Whether this variable is known to have constant initialization. This is
848  /// currently only computed in C++, for static / thread storage duration
849  /// variables that might have constant initialization and for variables that
850  /// are usable in constant expressions.
851  bool HasConstantInitialization : 1;
852 
853  /// Whether this variable is known to have constant destruction. That is,
854  /// whether running the destructor on the initial value is a side-effect
855  /// (and doesn't inspect any state that might have changed during program
856  /// execution). This is currently only computed if the destructor is
857  /// non-trivial.
858  bool HasConstantDestruction : 1;
859 
860  /// In C++98, whether the initializer is an ICE. This affects whether the
861  /// variable is usable in constant expressions.
862  bool HasICEInit : 1;
863  bool CheckedForICEInit : 1;
864 
865  Stmt *Value;
866  APValue Evaluated;
867 
868  EvaluatedStmt()
869  : WasEvaluated(false), IsEvaluating(false),
870  HasConstantInitialization(false), HasConstantDestruction(false),
871  HasICEInit(false), CheckedForICEInit(false) {}
872 };
873 
874 /// Represents a variable declaration or definition.
875 class VarDecl : public DeclaratorDecl, public Redeclarable<VarDecl> {
876 public:
877  /// Initialization styles.
878  enum InitializationStyle {
879  /// C-style initialization with assignment
880  CInit,
881 
882  /// Call-style initialization (C++98)
883  CallInit,
884 
885  /// Direct list-initialization (C++11)
886  ListInit
887  };
888 
889  /// Kinds of thread-local storage.
890  enum TLSKind {
891  /// Not a TLS variable.
892  TLS_None,
893 
894  /// TLS with a known-constant initializer.
895  TLS_Static,
896 
897  /// TLS with a dynamic initializer.
898  TLS_Dynamic
899  };
900 
901  /// Return the string used to specify the storage class \p SC.
902  ///
903  /// It is illegal to call this function with SC == None.
904  static const char *getStorageClassSpecifierString(StorageClass SC);
905 
906 protected:
907  // A pointer union of Stmt * and EvaluatedStmt *. When an EvaluatedStmt, we
908  // have allocated the auxiliary struct of information there.
909  //
910  // TODO: It is a bit unfortunate to use a PointerUnion inside the VarDecl for
911  // this as *many* VarDecls are ParmVarDecls that don't have default
912  // arguments. We could save some space by moving this pointer union to be
913  // allocated in trailing space when necessary.
914  using InitType = llvm::PointerUnion<Stmt *, EvaluatedStmt *>;
915 
916  /// The initializer for this variable or, for a ParmVarDecl, the
917  /// C++ default argument.
918  mutable InitType Init;

922  friend class ASTNodeImporter;

925  class VarDeclBitfields {

927  friend class VarDecl;
928 
929  unsigned SClass : 3;
930  unsigned TSCSpec : 2;
931  unsigned InitStyle : 2;
932 
933  /// Whether this variable is an ARC pseudo-__strong variable; see
934  /// isARCPseudoStrong() for details.
935  unsigned ARCPseudoStrong : 1;
936  };

951  class ParmVarDeclBitfields {
952  friend class ASTDeclReader;
953  friend class ParmVarDecl;
954 
955  unsigned : NumVarDeclBits;
956 
957  /// Whether this parameter inherits a default argument from a
958  /// prior declaration.
959  unsigned HasInheritedDefaultArg : 1;
960 
961  /// Describes the kind of default argument for this parameter. By default
962  /// this is none. If this is normal, then the default argument is stored in
963  /// the \c VarDecl initializer expression unless we were unable to parse
964  /// (even an invalid) expression for the default argument.
965  unsigned DefaultArgKind : 2;
966 
967  /// Whether this parameter undergoes K&R argument promotion.
968  unsigned IsKNRPromoted : 1;
969 
970  /// Whether this parameter is an ObjC method parameter or not.
971  unsigned IsObjCMethodParam : 1;
972 
973  /// If IsObjCMethodParam, a Decl::ObjCDeclQualifier.
974  /// Otherwise, the number of function parameter scopes enclosing
975  /// the function parameter scope in which this parameter was
976  /// declared.
977  unsigned ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals : NumScopeDepthOrObjCQualsBits;
978 
979  /// The number of parameters preceding this parameter in the
980  /// function parameter scope in which it was declared.
981  unsigned ParameterIndex : NumParameterIndexBits;
982  };
983 
984  class NonParmVarDeclBitfields {
985  friend class ASTDeclReader;
986  friend class ImplicitParamDecl;
987  friend class VarDecl;
988 
989  unsigned : NumVarDeclBits;
990 
991  // FIXME: We need something similar to CXXRecordDecl::DefinitionData.
992  /// Whether this variable is a definition which was demoted due to
993  /// module merge.
994  unsigned IsThisDeclarationADemotedDefinition : 1;
995 
996  /// Whether this variable is the exception variable in a C++ catch
997  /// or an Objective-C @catch statement.
998  unsigned ExceptionVar : 1;
999 
1000  /// Whether this local variable could be allocated in the return
1001  /// slot of its function, enabling the named return value optimization
1002  /// (NRVO).
1003  unsigned NRVOVariable : 1;
1004 
1005  /// Whether this variable is the for-range-declaration in a C++0x
1006  /// for-range statement.
1007  unsigned CXXForRangeDecl : 1;
1008 
1009  /// Whether this variable is the for-in loop declaration in Objective-C.
1010  unsigned ObjCForDecl : 1;
1011 
1012  /// Whether this variable is (C++1z) inline.
1013  unsigned IsInline : 1;
1014 
1015  /// Whether this variable has (C++1z) inline explicitly specified.
1016  unsigned IsInlineSpecified : 1;
1017 
1018  /// Whether this variable is (C++0x) constexpr.
1019  unsigned IsConstexpr : 1;
1020 
1021  /// Whether this variable is the implicit variable for a lambda
1022  /// init-capture.
1023  unsigned IsInitCapture : 1;
1024 
1025  /// Whether this local extern variable's previous declaration was
1026  /// declared in the same block scope. This controls whether we should merge
1027  /// the type of this declaration with its previous declaration.
1028  unsigned PreviousDeclInSameBlockScope : 1;
1029 
1030  /// Defines kind of the ImplicitParamDecl: 'this', 'self', 'vtt', '_cmd' or
1031  /// something else.
1032  unsigned ImplicitParamKind : 3;
1033 
1034  unsigned EscapingByref : 1;
1035  };

1082  /// Returns the storage class as written in the source. For the
1083  /// computed linkage of symbol, see getLinkage.
1084  StorageClass getStorageClass() const {
1085  return (StorageClass) VarDeclBits.SClass;
1086  }
1087  void setStorageClass(StorageClass SC);
1088 
1089  void setTSCSpec(ThreadStorageClassSpecifier TSC) {
1090  VarDeclBits.TSCSpec = TSC;
1091  assert(VarDeclBits.TSCSpec == TSC && "truncation");
1092  }
1093  ThreadStorageClassSpecifier getTSCSpec() const {
1094  return static_cast<ThreadStorageClassSpecifier>(VarDeclBits.TSCSpec);
1095  }
1096  TLSKind getTLSKind() const;
1097 
1098  /// Returns true if a variable with function scope is a non-static local
1099  /// variable.
1100  bool hasLocalStorage() const {
1101  if (getStorageClass() == SC_None) {
1102  // OpenCL v1.2 s6.5.3: The __constant or constant address space name is
1103  // used to describe variables allocated in global memory and which are
1104  // accessed inside a kernel(s) as read-only variables. As such, variables
1105  // in constant address space cannot have local storage.
1106  if (getType().getAddressSpace() == LangAS::opencl_constant)
1107  return false;
1108  // Second check is for C++11 [dcl.stc]p4.
1109  return !isFileVarDecl() && getTSCSpec() == TSCS_unspecified;
1110  }
1111 
1112  // Global Named Register (GNU extension)
1113  if (getStorageClass() == SC_Register && !isLocalVarDeclOrParm())
1114  return false;
1115 
1116  // Return true for: Auto, Register.
1117  // Return false for: Extern, Static, PrivateExtern, OpenCLWorkGroupLocal.
1118 
1119  return getStorageClass() >= SC_Auto;
1120  }
1121 
1122  /// Returns true if a variable with function scope is a static local
1123  /// variable.
1124  bool isStaticLocal() const {
1125  return (getStorageClass() == SC_Static ||
1126  // C++11 [dcl.stc]p4
1127  (getStorageClass() == SC_None && getTSCSpec() == TSCS_thread_local))
1128  && !isFileVarDecl();
1129  }
1130 
1131  /// Returns true if a variable has extern or __private_extern__
1132  /// storage.
1133  bool hasExternalStorage() const {
1134  return getStorageClass() == SC_Extern ||
1135  getStorageClass() == SC_PrivateExtern;
1136  }
1137 
1138  /// Returns true for all variables that do not have local storage.
1139  ///
1140  /// This includes all global variables as well as static variables declared
1141  /// within a function.
1142  bool hasGlobalStorage() const { return !hasLocalStorage(); }
1143 
1144  /// Get the storage duration of this variable, per C++ [basic.stc].
1145  StorageDuration getStorageDuration() const {
1146  return hasLocalStorage() ? SD_Automatic :
1147  getTSCSpec() ? SD_Thread : SD_Static;
1148  }
1149 
1150  /// Compute the language linkage.
1151  LanguageLinkage getLanguageLinkage() const;
1152 
1153  /// Determines whether this variable is a variable with external, C linkage.
1154  bool isExternC() const;
1155 
1156  /// Determines whether this variable's context is, or is nested within,
1157  /// a C++ extern "C" linkage spec.
1158  bool isInExternCContext() const;
1159 
1160  /// Determines whether this variable's context is, or is nested within,
1161  /// a C++ extern "C++" linkage spec.
1162  bool isInExternCXXContext() const;
1163 
1164  /// Returns true for local variable declarations other than parameters.
1165  /// Note that this includes static variables inside of functions. It also
1166  /// includes variables inside blocks.
1167  ///
1168  /// void foo() { int x; static int y; extern int z; }
1169  bool isLocalVarDecl() const {
1170  if (getKind() != Decl::Var && getKind() != Decl::Decomposition)
1171  return false;
1172  if (const DeclContext *DC = getLexicalDeclContext())
1173  return DC->getRedeclContext()->isFunctionOrMethod();
1174  return false;
1175  }
1176 
1177  /// Similar to isLocalVarDecl but also includes parameters.
1178  bool isLocalVarDeclOrParm() const {
1179  return isLocalVarDecl() || getKind() == Decl::ParmVar;
1180  }
1181 
1182  /// Similar to isLocalVarDecl, but excludes variables declared in blocks.
1183  bool isFunctionOrMethodVarDecl() const {
1184  if (getKind() != Decl::Var && getKind() != Decl::Decomposition)
1185  return false;
1186  const DeclContext *DC = getLexicalDeclContext()->getRedeclContext();
1187  return DC->isFunctionOrMethod() && DC->getDeclKind() != Decl::Block;
1188  }
1189 
1190  /// Determines whether this is a static data member.
1191  ///
1192  /// This will only be true in C++, and applies to, e.g., the
1193  /// variable 'x' in:
1194  /// \code
1195  /// struct S {
1196  /// static int x;
1197  /// };
1198  /// \endcode
1199  bool isStaticDataMember() const {
1200  // If it wasn't static, it would be a FieldDecl.
1201  return getKind() != Decl::ParmVar && getDeclContext()->isRecord();
1202  }

1257  /// Returns true for file scoped variable declaration.

1259  Kind K = getKind();
1260  if (K == ParmVar || K == ImplicitParam)
1261  return false;

1264  return true;

1267  return true;

1319  /// Attempt to evaluate the value of the initializer attached to this
1320  /// declaration, and produce notes explaining why it cannot be evaluated.
1321  /// Returns a pointer to the value if evaluation succeeded, 0 otherwise.
1322  APValue *evaluateValue() const;
1323 
1324 private:
1325  APValue *evaluateValueImpl(SmallVectorImpl<PartialDiagnosticAt> &Notes,
1326  bool IsConstantInitialization) const;
1327 
1328 public:
1329  /// Return the already-evaluated value of this variable's
1330  /// initializer, or NULL if the value is not yet known. Returns pointer
1331  /// to untyped APValue if the value could not be evaluated.
1332  APValue *getEvaluatedValue() const;
1333 
1334  /// Evaluate the destruction of this variable to determine if it constitutes
1335  /// constant destruction.
1336  ///
1337  /// \pre hasConstantInitialization()
1338  /// \return \c true if this variable has constant destruction, \c false if
1339  /// not.
1340  bool evaluateDestruction(SmallVectorImpl<PartialDiagnosticAt> &Notes) const;
1341 
1342  /// Determine whether this variable has constant initialization.
1343  ///
1344  /// This is only set in two cases: when the language semantics require
1345  /// constant initialization (globals in C and some globals in C++), and when
1346  /// the variable is usable in constant expressions (constexpr, const int, and
1347  /// reference variables in C++).
1348  bool hasConstantInitialization() const;

1351  /// expression. For use in C++98, where this affects whether the variable is
1352  /// usable in constant expressions.
1353  bool hasICEInitializer(const ASTContext &Context) const;
1354 
1355  /// Evaluate the initializer of this variable to determine whether it's a
1356  /// constant initializer. Should only be called once, after completing the
1357  /// definition of the variable.
1358  bool checkForConstantInitialization(
1359  SmallVectorImpl<PartialDiagnosticAt> &Notes) const;
1360 
1361  void setInitStyle(InitializationStyle Style) {
1362  VarDeclBits.InitStyle = Style;
1363  }
1364 
1365  /// The style of initialization for this declaration.
1366  ///
1367  /// C-style initialization is "int x = 1;". Call-style initialization is
1368  /// a C++98 direct-initializer, e.g. "int x(1);". The Init expression will be
1369  /// the expression inside the parens or a "ClassType(a,b,c)" class constructor
1370  /// expression for class types. List-style initialization is C++11 syntax,
1371  /// e.g. "int x{1};". Clients can distinguish between different forms of
1372  /// initialization by checking this value. In particular, "int x = {1};" is
1373  /// C-style, "int x({1})" is call-style, and "int x{1};" is list-style; the
1374  /// Init expression in all three cases is an InitListExpr.
1375  InitializationStyle getInitStyle() const {
1376  return static_cast<InitializationStyle>(VarDeclBits.InitStyle);
1377  }
1378 
1379  /// Whether the initializer is a direct-initializer (list or call).
1380  bool isDirectInit() const {
1381  return getInitStyle() != CInit;
1382  }
1383 
1384  /// If this definition should pretend to be a declaration.
1385  bool isThisDeclarationADemotedDefinition() const {
1386  return isa<ParmVarDecl>(this) ? false :
1387  NonParmVarDeclBits.IsThisDeclarationADemotedDefinition;
1388  }
1389 
1390  /// This is a definition which should be demoted to a declaration.
1391  ///
1392  /// In some cases (mostly module merging) we can end up with two visible
1393  /// definitions one of which needs to be demoted to a declaration to keep
1394  /// the AST invariants.
1395  void demoteThisDefinitionToDeclaration() {
1396  assert(isThisDeclarationADefinition() && "Not a definition!");
1397  assert(!isa<ParmVarDecl>(this) && "Cannot demote ParmVarDecls!");
1398  NonParmVarDeclBits.IsThisDeclarationADemotedDefinition = 1;
1399  }

1411  /// Determine whether this local variable can be used with the named
1412  /// return value optimization (NRVO).
1413  ///
1414  /// The named return value optimization (NRVO) works by marking certain
1415  /// non-volatile local variables of class type as NRVO objects. These
1416  /// locals can be allocated within the return slot of their containing
1417  /// function, in which case there is no need to copy the object to the
1418  /// return slot when returning from the function. Within the function body,
1419  /// each return that returns the NRVO object will have this variable as its
1420  /// NRVO candidate.

1422  return isa<ParmVarDecl>(this) ? false : NonParmVarDeclBits.NRVOVariable;
1423  }

1427  }

1663 /// Represents a parameter to a function.
1664 class ParmVarDecl : public VarDecl {

1666  enum { MaxFunctionScopeDepth = 255 };
1667  enum { MaxFunctionScopeIndex = 255 };
1668 
1669 protected:
1670  ParmVarDecl(Kind DK, ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation StartLoc,
1671  SourceLocation IdLoc, IdentifierInfo *Id, QualType T,
1672  TypeSourceInfo *TInfo, StorageClass S, Expr *DefArg)
1673  : VarDecl(DK, C, DC, StartLoc, IdLoc, Id, T, TInfo, S) {
1674  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.HasInheritedDefaultArg == false);
1675  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.DefaultArgKind == DAK_None);
1676  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.IsKNRPromoted == false);
1677  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam == false);
1678  setDefaultArg(DefArg);
1679  }
1680 
1681 public:
1682  static ParmVarDecl *Create(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
1683  SourceLocation StartLoc,
1684  SourceLocation IdLoc, IdentifierInfo *Id,
1685  QualType T, TypeSourceInfo *TInfo,
1686  StorageClass S, Expr *DefArg);

1689 
1690  SourceRange getSourceRange() const override LLVM_READONLY;
1691 
1692  void setObjCMethodScopeInfo(unsigned parameterIndex) {
1693  ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam = true;
1694  setParameterIndex(parameterIndex);
1695  }

1698  assert(!ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam);
1699 
1700  ParmVarDeclBits.ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals = scopeDepth;
1701  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals == scopeDepth
1702  && "truncation!");
1703

1705  }

1708  return ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam;
1709  }
1710 
1711  /// Determines whether this parameter is destroyed in the callee function.
1712  bool isDestroyedInCallee() const;
1713 
1714  unsigned getFunctionScopeDepth() const {
1715  if (ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam) return 0;
1716  return ParmVarDeclBits.ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals;
1717  }
1718 
1719  static constexpr unsigned getMaxFunctionScopeDepth() {
1720  return (1u << NumScopeDepthOrObjCQualsBits) - 1;
1721  }
1722 
1723  /// Returns the index of this parameter in its prototype or method scope.
1724  unsigned getFunctionScopeIndex() const {
1725  return getParameterIndex();
1726  }
1727 
1728  ObjCDeclQualifier getObjCDeclQualifier() const {
1729  if (!ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam) return OBJC_TQ_None;
1730  return ObjCDeclQualifier(ParmVarDeclBits.ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals);
1731  }
1732  void setObjCDeclQualifier(ObjCDeclQualifier QTVal) {
1733  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.IsObjCMethodParam);
1734  ParmVarDeclBits.ScopeDepthOrObjCQuals = QTVal;
1735  }
1736 
1737  /// True if the value passed to this parameter must undergo
1738  /// K&R-style default argument promotion:
1739  ///
1740  /// C99 6.5.2.2.
1741  /// If the expression that denotes the called function has a type
1742  /// that does not include a prototype, the integer promotions are
1743  /// performed on each argument, and arguments that have type float
1744  /// are promoted to double.
1745  bool isKNRPromoted() const {
1746  return ParmVarDeclBits.IsKNRPromoted;
1747  }

1749  ParmVarDeclBits.IsKNRPromoted = promoted;
1750  }

1752  Expr *getDefaultArg();

1754  return const_cast<ParmVarDecl *>(this)->getDefaultArg();
1755  }

1760  /// argument.

1763  Expr *getUninstantiatedDefaultArg();

1765  return const_cast<ParmVarDecl *>(this)->getUninstantiatedDefaultArg();
1766  }
1767 
1768  /// Determines whether this parameter has a default argument,
1769  /// either parsed or not.
1770  bool hasDefaultArg() const;
1771 
1772  /// Determines whether this parameter has a default argument that has not
1773  /// yet been parsed. This will occur during the processing of a C++ class
1774  /// whose member functions have default arguments, e.g.,
1775  /// @code
1776  /// class X {
1777  /// public:
1778  /// void f(int x = 17); // x has an unparsed default argument now
1779  /// }; // x has a regular default argument now
1780  /// @endcode
1781  bool hasUnparsedDefaultArg() const {
1782  return ParmVarDeclBits.DefaultArgKind == DAK_Unparsed;
1783  }
1784

1786  return ParmVarDeclBits.DefaultArgKind == DAK_Uninstantiated;
1787  }
1788

1790  /// The argument will be replaced with a real default argument via
1791  /// setDefaultArg when the class definition enclosing the function
1792  /// declaration that owns this default argument is completed.
1793  void setUnparsedDefaultArg() {
1794  ParmVarDeclBits.DefaultArgKind = DAK_Unparsed;
1795  }
1796

1798  return ParmVarDeclBits.HasInheritedDefaultArg;
1799  }

1802  ParmVarDeclBits.HasInheritedDefaultArg = I;
1803  }

1805  QualType getOriginalType() const;

1807  /// Sets the function declaration that owns this
1808  /// ParmVarDecl. Since ParmVarDecls are often created before the
1809  /// FunctionDecls that own them, this routine is required to update
1810  /// the DeclContext appropriately.
1811  void setOwningFunction(DeclContext *FD) { setDeclContext(FD); }
1812 
1813  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
1814  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
1815  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == ParmVar; }
1816 
1817 private:
1818  enum { ParameterIndexSentinel = (1 << NumParameterIndexBits) - 1 };
1819 
1820  void setParameterIndex(unsigned parameterIndex) {
1821  if (parameterIndex >= ParameterIndexSentinel) {
1822  setParameterIndexLarge(parameterIndex);
1823  return;
1824  }
1825 
1826  ParmVarDeclBits.ParameterIndex = parameterIndex;
1827  assert(ParmVarDeclBits.ParameterIndex == parameterIndex && "truncation!");
1828  }
1829  unsigned getParameterIndex() const {
1830  unsigned d = ParmVarDeclBits.ParameterIndex;
1831  return d == ParameterIndexSentinel ? getParameterIndexLarge() : d;
1832  }
1833 
1834  void setParameterIndexLarge(unsigned parameterIndex);
1835  unsigned getParameterIndexLarge() const;
1836 };

1838 enum class MultiVersionKind {
1839  None,
1840  Target,
1841  CPUSpecific,
1842  CPUDispatch,
1843  TargetClones
1844 };
1845 
1846 /// Represents a function declaration or definition.
1847 ///
1848 /// Since a given function can be declared several times in a program,
1849 /// there may be several FunctionDecls that correspond to that
1850 /// function. Only one of those FunctionDecls will be found when
1851 /// traversing the list of declarations in the context of the
1852 /// FunctionDecl (e.g., the translation unit); this FunctionDecl
1853 /// contains all of the information known about the function. Other,
1854 /// previous declarations of the function are available via the
1855 /// getPreviousDecl() chain.
1856 class FunctionDecl : public DeclaratorDecl,
1857  public DeclContext,
1858  public Redeclarable<FunctionDecl> {
1859  // This class stores some data in DeclContext::FunctionDeclBits
1860  // to save some space. Use the provided accessors to access it.
1861 public:
1862  /// The kind of templated function a FunctionDecl can be.
1863  enum TemplatedKind {
1864  // Not templated.
1865  TK_NonTemplate,
1866  // The pattern in a function template declaration.
1867  TK_FunctionTemplate,
1868  // A non-template function that is an instantiation or explicit
1869  // specialization of a member of a templated class.
1870  TK_MemberSpecialization,
1871  // An instantiation or explicit specialization of a function template.
1872  // Note: this might have been instantiated from a templated class if it
1873  // is a class-scope explicit specialization.
1874  TK_FunctionTemplateSpecialization,
1875  // A function template specialization that hasn't yet been resolved to a
1876  // particular specialized function template.
1877  TK_DependentFunctionTemplateSpecialization
1878  };
1879 
1880  /// Stashed information about a defaulted function definition whose body has
1881  /// not yet been lazily generated.
1882  class DefaultedFunctionInfo final
1883  : llvm::TrailingObjects<DefaultedFunctionInfo, DeclAccessPair> {
1884  friend TrailingObjects;
1885  unsigned NumLookups;
1886 
1887  public:
1888  static DefaultedFunctionInfo *Create(ASTContext &Context,
1889  ArrayRef<DeclAccessPair> Lookups);
1890  /// Get the unqualified lookup results that should be used in this
1891  /// defaulted function definition.
1892  ArrayRef<DeclAccessPair> getUnqualifiedLookups() const {
1893  return {getTrailingObjects<DeclAccessPair>(), NumLookups};
1894  }
1895  };
1896 
1897 private:
1898  /// A new[]'d array of pointers to VarDecls for the formal
1899  /// parameters of this function. This is null if a prototype or if there are
1900  /// no formals.
1901  ParmVarDecl **ParamInfo = nullptr;
1902 
1903  /// The active member of this union is determined by
1904  /// FunctionDeclBits.HasDefaultedFunctionInfo.
1905  union {
1906  /// The body of the function.
1907  LazyDeclStmtPtr Body;
1908  /// Information about a future defaulted function definition.
1909  DefaultedFunctionInfo *DefaultedInfo;
1910  };
1911 
1912  unsigned ODRHash;
1913 
1914  /// End part of this FunctionDecl's source range.
1915  ///
1916  /// We could compute the full range in getSourceRange(). However, when we're
1917  /// dealing with a function definition deserialized from a PCH/AST file,
1918  /// we can only compute the full range once the function body has been
1919  /// de-serialized, so it's far better to have the (sometimes-redundant)
1920  /// EndRangeLoc.

1923  /// The template or declaration that this declaration
1924  /// describes or was instantiated from, respectively.
1925  ///
1926  /// For non-templates, this value will be NULL. For function
1927  /// declarations that describe a function template, this will be a

2069  // Function definitions.
2070  //
2071  // A function declaration may be:
2072  // - a non defining declaration,
2073  // - a definition. A function may be defined because:
2074  // - it has a body, or will have it in the case of late parsing.
2075  // - it has an uninstantiated body. The body does not exist because the
2076  // function is not used yet, but the declaration is considered a
2077  // definition and does not allow other definition of this function.
2078  // - it does not have a user specified body, but it does not allow
2079  // redefinition, because it is deleted/defaulted or is defined through
2080  // some other mechanism (alias, ifunc).
2081 
2082  /// Returns true if the function has a body.
2083  ///
2084  /// The function body might be in any of the (re-)declarations of this
2085  /// function. The variant that accepts a FunctionDecl pointer will set that
2086  /// function declaration to the actual declaration containing the body (if
2087  /// there is one).
2088  bool hasBody(const FunctionDecl *&Definition) const;
2089 
2090  bool hasBody() const override {
2091  const FunctionDecl* Definition;
2092  return hasBody(Definition);
2093  }
2094 
2095  /// Returns whether the function has a trivial body that does not require any
2096  /// specific codegen.
2097  bool hasTrivialBody() const;
2098 
2099  /// Returns true if the function has a definition that does not need to be
2100  /// instantiated.
2101  ///
2102  /// The variant that accepts a FunctionDecl pointer will set that function
2103  /// declaration to the declaration that is a definition (if there is one).
2104  ///
2105  /// \param CheckForPendingFriendDefinition If \c true, also check for friend
2106  /// declarations that were instantiataed from function definitions.
2107  /// Such a declaration behaves as if it is a definition for the
2108  /// purpose of redefinition checking, but isn't actually a "real"
2109  /// definition until its body is instantiated.
2110  bool isDefined(const FunctionDecl *&Definition,
2111  bool CheckForPendingFriendDefinition = false) const;
2112 
2113  bool isDefined() const {
2114  const FunctionDecl* Definition;
2115  return isDefined(Definition);
2116  }
2117 
2118  /// Get the definition for this declaration.
2119  FunctionDecl *getDefinition() {
2120  const FunctionDecl *Definition;
2121  if (isDefined(Definition))
2122  return const_cast<FunctionDecl *>(Definition);
2123  return nullptr;
2124  }
2125  const FunctionDecl *getDefinition() const {
2126  return const_cast<FunctionDecl *>(this)->getDefinition();
2127  }
2128 
2129  /// Retrieve the body (definition) of the function. The function body might be
2130  /// in any of the (re-)declarations of this function. The variant that accepts
2131  /// a FunctionDecl pointer will set that function declaration to the actual
2132  /// declaration containing the body (if there is one).
2133  /// NOTE: For checking if there is a body, use hasBody() instead, to avoid
2134  /// unnecessary AST de-serialization of the body.
2135  Stmt *getBody(const FunctionDecl *&Definition) const;
2136 
2137  Stmt *getBody() const override {
2138  const FunctionDecl* Definition;
2139  return getBody(Definition);
2140  }

2142  /// Returns whether this specific declaration of the function is also a
2143  /// definition that does not contain uninstantiated body.
2144  ///
2145  /// This does not determine whether the function has been defined (e.g., in a
2146  /// previous definition); for that information, use isDefined.
2147  ///
2148  /// Note: the function declaration does not become a definition until the
2149  /// parser reaches the definition, if called before, this function will return
2150  /// `false`.

2153  doesThisDeclarationHaveABody() || hasSkippedBody() ||
2154  willHaveBody() || hasDefiningAttr();

2299  /// Whether the instantiation of this function is pending.
2300  /// This bit is set when the decision to instantiate this function is made
2301  /// and unset if and when the function body is created. That leaves out
2302  /// cases where instantiation did not happen because the template definition
2303  /// was not seen in this TU. This bit remains set in those cases, under the

2319  /// Whether this function has been deleted.
2320  ///
2321  /// A function that is "deleted" (via the C++0x "= delete" syntax)
2322  /// acts like a normal function, except that it cannot actually be
2323  /// called or have its address taken. Deleted functions are
2324  /// typically used in C++ overload resolution to attract arguments
2325  /// whose type or lvalue/rvalue-ness would permit the use of a
2326  /// different overload that would behave incorrectly. For example,
2327  /// one might use deleted functions to ban implicit conversion from
2328  /// a floating-point number to an Integer type:
2329  ///
2330  /// @code
2331  /// struct Integer {
2332  /// Integer(long); // construct from a long
2333  /// Integer(double) = delete; // no construction from float or double
2334  /// Integer(long double) = delete; // no construction from long double
2335  /// };
2336  /// @endcode
2337  // If a function is deleted, its first declaration must be.
2338  bool isDeleted() const {
2339  return getCanonicalDecl()->FunctionDeclBits.IsDeleted;
2340  }
2341 
2342  bool isDeletedAsWritten() const {
2343  return FunctionDeclBits.IsDeleted && !isDefaulted();
2344  }
2345 
2346  void setDeletedAsWritten(bool D = true) { FunctionDeclBits.IsDeleted = D; }

2356  /// Determines whether this operator new or delete is one
2357  /// of the reserved global placement operators:
2358  /// void *operator new(size_t, void *);
2359  /// void *operator new[](size_t, void *);
2360  /// void operator delete(void *, void *);
2361  /// void operator delete[](void *, void *);
2362  /// These functions have special behavior under [new.delete.placement]:
2363  /// These functions are reserved, a C++ program may not define
2364  /// functions that displace the versions in the Standard C++ library.
2365  /// The provisions of [basic.stc.dynamic] do not apply to these
2366  /// reserved placement forms of operator new and operator delete.
2367  ///
2368  /// This function must be an allocation or deallocation function.
2369  bool isReservedGlobalPlacementOperator() const;
2370 
2371  /// Determines whether this function is one of the replaceable
2372  /// global allocation functions:
2373  /// void *operator new(size_t);
2374  /// void *operator new(size_t, const std::nothrow_t &) noexcept;
2375  /// void *operator new[](size_t);
2376  /// void *operator new[](size_t, const std::nothrow_t &) noexcept;
2377  /// void operator delete(void *) noexcept;
2378  /// void operator delete(void *, std::size_t) noexcept; [C++1y]
2379  /// void operator delete(void *, const std::nothrow_t &) noexcept;
2380  /// void operator delete[](void *) noexcept;
2381  /// void operator delete[](void *, std::size_t) noexcept; [C++1y]
2382  /// void operator delete[](void *, const std::nothrow_t &) noexcept;
2383  /// These functions have special behavior under C++1y [expr.new]:
2384  /// An implementation is allowed to omit a call to a replaceable global
2385  /// allocation function. [...]
2386  ///
2387  /// If this function is an aligned allocation/deallocation function, return
2388  /// the parameter number of the requested alignment through AlignmentParam.
2389  ///
2390  /// If this function is an allocation/deallocation function that takes
2391  /// the `std::nothrow_t` tag, return true through IsNothrow,
2392  bool isReplaceableGlobalAllocationFunction(

2523  /// may be fewer than the number of function parameters, if some of the

2637  /// If this function is an instantiation of a member function
2638  /// of a class template specialization, retrieves the function from
2639  /// which it was instantiated.
2640  ///
2641  /// This routine will return non-NULL for (non-templated) member
2642  /// functions of class templates and for instantiations of function
2643  /// templates. For example, given:
2644  ///
2645  /// \code
2646  /// template<typename T>
2647  /// struct X {
2648  /// void f(T);
2649  /// };
2650  /// \endcode
2651  ///
2652  /// The declaration for X<int>::f is a (non-templated) FunctionDecl
2653  /// whose parent is the class template specialization X<int>. For
2654  /// this declaration, getInstantiatedFromFunction() will return

2656  /// X<int>::A is required, it will be instantiated from the
2657  /// declaration returned by getInstantiatedFromMemberFunction().

2838 /// Represents a member of a struct/union/class.
2839 class FieldDecl : public DeclaratorDecl, public Mergeable<FieldDecl> {
2840  unsigned BitField : 1;
2841  unsigned Mutable : 1;
2842  mutable unsigned CachedFieldIndex : 30;
2843 
2844  /// The kinds of value we can store in InitializerOrBitWidth.
2845  ///
2846  /// Note that this is compatible with InClassInitStyle except for
2847  /// ISK_CapturedVLAType.
2848  enum InitStorageKind {
2849  /// If the pointer is null, there's nothing special. Otherwise,
2850  /// this is a bitfield and the pointer is the Expr* storing the
2851  /// bit-width.
2852  ISK_NoInit = (unsigned) ICIS_NoInit,
2853 
2854  /// The pointer is an (optional due to delayed parsing) Expr*
2855  /// holding the copy-initializer.
2856  ISK_InClassCopyInit = (unsigned) ICIS_CopyInit,
2857 
2858  /// The pointer is an (optional due to delayed parsing) Expr*
2859  /// holding the list-initializer.
2860  ISK_InClassListInit = (unsigned) ICIS_ListInit,
2861 
2862  /// The pointer is a VariableArrayType* that's been captured;
2863  /// the enclosing context is a lambda or captured statement.
2864  ISK_CapturedVLAType,
2865  };
2866 
2867  /// If this is a bitfield with a default member initializer, this
2868  /// structure is used to represent the two expressions.
2869  struct InitAndBitWidth {
2870  Expr *Init;
2871  Expr *BitWidth;
2872  };
2873 
2874  /// Storage for either the bit-width, the in-class initializer, or
2875  /// both (via InitAndBitWidth), or the captured variable length array bound.
2876  ///
2877  /// If the storage kind is ISK_InClassCopyInit or
2878  /// ISK_InClassListInit, but the initializer is null, then this
2879  /// field has an in-class initializer that has not yet been parsed
2880  /// and attached.
2881  // FIXME: Tail-allocate this to reduce the size of FieldDecl in the
2882  // overwhelmingly common case that we have none of these things.
2883  llvm::PointerIntPair<void *, 2, InitStorageKind> InitStorage;
2884 
2885 protected:
2886  FieldDecl(Kind DK, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation StartLoc,
2887  SourceLocation IdLoc, IdentifierInfo *Id,
2888  QualType T, TypeSourceInfo *TInfo, Expr *BW, bool Mutable,
2889  InClassInitStyle InitStyle)
2890  : DeclaratorDecl(DK, DC, IdLoc, Id, T, TInfo, StartLoc),
2891  BitField(false), Mutable(Mutable), CachedFieldIndex(0),
2892  InitStorage(nullptr, (InitStorageKind) InitStyle) {
2893  if (BW)
2894  setBitWidth(BW);
2895  }
2896 
2897 public:
2898  friend class ASTDeclReader;
2899  friend class ASTDeclWriter;
2900 
2901  static FieldDecl *Create(const ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
2902  SourceLocation StartLoc, SourceLocation IdLoc,
2903  IdentifierInfo *Id, QualType T,
2904  TypeSourceInfo *TInfo, Expr *BW, bool Mutable,
2905  InClassInitStyle InitStyle);
2906 
2907  static FieldDecl *CreateDeserialized(ASTContext &C, unsigned ID);
2908 
2909  /// Returns the index of this field within its record,
2910  /// as appropriate for passing to ASTRecordLayout::getFieldOffset.
2911  unsigned getFieldIndex() const;
2912 
2913  /// Determines whether this field is mutable (C++ only).
2914  bool isMutable() const { return Mutable; }
2915 
2916  /// Determines whether this field is a bitfield.
2917  bool isBitField() const { return BitField; }
2918 
2919  /// Determines whether this is an unnamed bitfield.
2920  bool isUnnamedBitfield() const { return isBitField() && !getDeclName(); }
2921 
2922  /// Determines whether this field is a
2923  /// representative for an anonymous struct or union. Such fields are
2924  /// unnamed and are implicitly generated by the implementation to
2925  /// store the data for the anonymous union or struct.
2926  bool isAnonymousStructOrUnion() const;
2927 
2928  Expr *getBitWidth() const {
2929  if (!BitField)
2930  return nullptr;
2931  void *Ptr = InitStorage.getPointer();
2932  if (getInClassInitStyle())
2933  return static_cast<InitAndBitWidth*>(Ptr)->BitWidth;
2934  return static_cast<Expr*>(Ptr);
2935  }
2936 
2937  unsigned getBitWidthValue(const ASTContext &Ctx) const;
2938 
2939  /// Set the bit-field width for this member.
2940  // Note: used by some clients (i.e., do not remove it).
2941  void setBitWidth(Expr *Width) {
2942  assert(!hasCapturedVLAType() && !BitField &&
2943  "bit width or captured type already set");
2944  assert(Width && "no bit width specified");
2945  InitStorage.setPointer(
2946  InitStorage.getInt()
2947  ? new (getASTContext())
2948  InitAndBitWidth{getInClassInitializer(), Width}
2949  : static_cast<void*>(Width));
2950  BitField = true;
2951  }
2952 
2953  /// Remove the bit-field width from this member.
2954  // Note: used by some clients (i.e., do not remove it).
2955  void removeBitWidth() {
2956  assert(isBitField() && "no bitfield width to remove");
2957  InitStorage.setPointer(getInClassInitializer());
2958  BitField = false;
2959  }
2960 
2961  /// Is this a zero-length bit-field? Such bit-fields aren't really bit-fields
2962  /// at all and instead act as a separator between contiguous runs of other
2963  /// bit-fields.
2964  bool isZeroLengthBitField(const ASTContext &Ctx) const;
2965 
2966  /// Determine if this field is a subobject of zero size, that is, either a
2967  /// zero-length bit-field or a field of empty class type with the
2968  /// [[no_unique_address]] attribute.
2969  bool isZeroSize(const ASTContext &Ctx) const;
2970 
2971  /// Get the kind of (C++11) default member initializer that this field has.
2972  InClassInitStyle getInClassInitStyle() const {
2973  InitStorageKind storageKind = InitStorage.getInt();
2974  return (storageKind == ISK_CapturedVLAType
2975  ? ICIS_NoInit : (InClassInitStyle) storageKind);
2976  }
2977 
2978  /// Determine whether this member has a C++11 default member initializer.
2979  bool hasInClassInitializer() const {
2980  return getInClassInitStyle() != ICIS_NoInit;
2981  }
2982 
2983  /// Get the C++11 default member initializer for this member, or null if one
2984  /// has not been set. If a valid declaration has a default member initializer,
2985  /// but this returns null, then we have not parsed and attached it yet.
2986  Expr *getInClassInitializer() const {
2987  if (!hasInClassInitializer())
2988  return nullptr;
2989  void *Ptr = InitStorage.getPointer();
2990  if (BitField)
2991  return static_cast<InitAndBitWidth*>(Ptr)->Init;
2992  return static_cast<Expr*>(Ptr);
2993  }
2994 
2995  /// Set the C++11 in-class initializer for this member.
2996  void setInClassInitializer(Expr *Init) {
2997  assert(hasInClassInitializer() && !getInClassInitializer());
2998  if (BitField)
2999  static_cast<InitAndBitWidth*>(InitStorage.getPointer())->Init = Init;
3000  else
3001  InitStorage.setPointer(Init);
3002  }
3003 
3004  /// Remove the C++11 in-class initializer from this member.
3005  void removeInClassInitializer() {
3006  assert(hasInClassInitializer() && "no initializer to remove");
3007  InitStorage.setPointerAndInt(getBitWidth(), ISK_NoInit);
3008  }
3009 
3010  /// Determine whether this member captures the variable length array
3011  /// type.
3012  bool hasCapturedVLAType() const {
3013  return InitStorage.getInt() == ISK_CapturedVLAType;
3014  }
3015 
3016  /// Get the captured variable length array type.
3017  const VariableArrayType *getCapturedVLAType() const {
3018  return hasCapturedVLAType() ? static_cast<const VariableArrayType *>(
3019  InitStorage.getPointer())
3020  : nullptr;
3021  }
3022 
3023  /// Set the captured variable length array type for this field.
3024  void setCapturedVLAType(const VariableArrayType *VLAType);
3025 
3026  /// Returns the parent of this field declaration, which
3027  /// is the struct in which this field is defined.
3028  ///
3029  /// Returns null if this is not a normal class/struct field declaration, e.g.
3030  /// ObjCAtDefsFieldDecl, ObjCIvarDecl.
3031  const RecordDecl *getParent() const {
3032  return dyn_cast<RecordDecl>(getDeclContext());
3033  }
3034 
3035  RecordDecl *getParent() {
3036  return dyn_cast<RecordDecl>(getDeclContext());
3037  }
3038 
3039  SourceRange getSourceRange() const override LLVM_READONLY;
3040 
3041  /// Retrieves the canonical declaration of this field.
3042  FieldDecl *getCanonicalDecl() override { return getFirstDecl(); }
3043  const FieldDecl *getCanonicalDecl() const { return getFirstDecl(); }
3044 
3045  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
3046  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
3047  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K >= firstField && K <= lastField; }
3048 };

3050 /// An instance of this object exists for each enum constant
3051 /// that is defined. For example, in "enum X {a,b}", each of a/b are
3052 /// EnumConstantDecl's, X is an instance of EnumDecl, and the type of a/b is a
3053 /// TagType for the X EnumDecl.
3054 class EnumConstantDecl : public ValueDecl, public Mergeable<EnumConstantDecl> {

3070  const llvm::APSInt &V);

3074  Expr *getInitExpr() { return (Expr*) Init; }

3097

3128  VarDecl *getVarDecl() const {
3129  assert(chain().size() >= 2);
3130  return dyn_cast<VarDecl>(chain().front());
3131  }
3132 
3133  IndirectFieldDecl *getCanonicalDecl() override { return getFirstDecl(); }
3134  const IndirectFieldDecl *getCanonicalDecl() const { return getFirstDecl(); }
3135 
3136  // Implement isa/cast/dyncast/etc.
3137  static bool classof(const Decl *D) { return classofKind(D->getKind()); }
3138  static bool classofKind(Kind K) { return K == IndirectField; }
3139 };

3183 /// Base class for declarations which introduce a typedef-name.
3184 class TypedefNameDecl : public TypeDecl, public Redeclarable<TypedefNameDecl> {
3185  struct alignas(8) ModedTInfo {
3186  TypeSourceInfo *first;

3188  };

3191  /// Otherwise, IsTransparentTag is (getInt() >> 1).

3194  MaybeModedTInfo;
3195

3265

3267  /// underlying tag type, as is the case with the NS_ENUM macro.
3268  bool isTransparentTag() const {
3269  if (MaybeModedTInfo.getInt())
3270  return MaybeModedTInfo.getInt() & 0x2;
3271  return isTransparentTagSlow();

3333  public DeclContext,

3541  /// Is this tag type named, either directly or via being defined in
3542  /// a typedef of this type?
3543  ///
3544  /// C++11 [basic.link]p8:
3545  /// A type is said to have linkage if and only if:
3546  /// - it is a class or enumeration type that is named (or has a
3547  /// name for linkage purposes) and the name has linkage; ...
3548  /// C++11 [dcl.typedef]p9:
3549  /// If the typedef declaration defines an unnamed class (or enum),
3550  /// the first typedef-name declared by the declaration to be that
3551  /// class type (or enum type) is used to denote the class type (or

3554  /// C does not have an analogous rule, but the same concept is
3555  /// nonetheless useful in some places.

3609 /// Represents an enum. In C++11, enums can be forward-declared
3610 /// with a fixed underlying type, and in C we allow them to be forward-declared
3611 /// with no underlying type as an extension.
3612 class EnumDecl : public TagDecl {
3613  // This class stores some data in DeclContext::EnumDeclBits
3614  // to save some space. Use the provided accessors to access it.
3615 
3616  /// This represent the integer type that the enum corresponds
3617  /// to for code generation purposes. Note that the enumerator constants may
3618  /// have a different type than this does.
3619  ///
3620  /// If the underlying integer type was explicitly stated in the source
3621  /// code, this is a TypeSourceInfo* for that type. Otherwise this type
3622  /// was automatically deduced somehow, and this is a Type*.
3623  ///
3624  /// Normally if IsFixed(), this would contain a TypeSourceInfo*, but in
3625  /// some cases it won't.
3626  ///
3627  /// The underlying type of an enumeration never has any qualifiers, so
3628  /// we can get away with just storing a raw Type*, and thus save an
3629  /// extra pointer when TypeSourceInfo is needed.
3630  llvm::PointerUnion<const Type *, TypeSourceInfo *> IntegerType;
3631 
3632  /// The integer type that values of this type should
3633  /// promote to. In C, enumerators are generally of an integer type
3634  /// directly, but gcc-style large enumerators (and all enumerators
3635  /// in C++) are of the enum type instead.
3636  QualType PromotionType;
3637 
3638  /// If this enumeration is an instantiation of a member enumeration
3639  /// of a class template specialization, this is the member specialization
3640  /// information.
3641  MemberSpecializationInfo *SpecializationInfo = nullptr;
3642 
3643  /// Store the ODRHash after first calculation.
3644  /// The corresponding flag HasODRHash is in EnumDeclBits
3645  /// and can be accessed with the provided accessors.
3646  unsigned ODRHash;
3647 
3648  EnumDecl(ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC, SourceLocation StartLoc,
3649  SourceLocation IdLoc, IdentifierInfo *Id, EnumDecl *PrevDecl,
3650  bool Scoped, bool ScopedUsingClassTag, bool Fixed);

3655  TemplateSpecializationKind TSK);

3658  /// non-negative enumerators of this enum.

3660  EnumDeclBits.NumPositiveBits = Num;
3661  assert(EnumDeclBits.NumPositiveBits == Num && "can't store this bitcount");
3662  }
3663

3665  /// negative enumerators of this enum. (see getNumNegativeBits)
3666  void setNumNegativeBits(unsigned Num) { EnumDeclBits.NumNegativeBits = Num; }
3667 
3668 public:
3669  /// True if this tag declaration is a scoped enumeration. Only
3670  /// possible in C++11 mode.
3671  void setScoped(bool Scoped = true) { EnumDeclBits.IsScoped = Scoped; }
3672 
3673  /// If this tag declaration is a scoped enum,
3674  /// then this is true if the scoped enum was declared using the class
3675  /// tag, false if it was declared with the struct tag. No meaning is
3676  /// associated if this tag declaration is not a scoped enum.
3677  void setScopedUsingClassTag(bool ScopedUCT = true) {
3678  EnumDeclBits.IsScopedUsingClassTag = ScopedUCT;

3731  /// forward-declared enum. This method is used to mark the
3732  /// declaration as being defined; its enumerators have already been
3733  /// added (via DeclContext::addDecl). NewType is the new underlying
3734  /// type of the enumeration type.

3736  QualType PromotionType,

3740  // Iterates through the enumerators of this enumeration.

3747  }

3750  const EnumDecl *E = getDefinition();
3751  if (!E)
3752  E = this;
3753  return enumerator_iterator(E->decls_begin());
3754  }
3755

3769  /// Return the integer type this enum decl corresponds to.
3770  /// This returns a null QualType for an enum forward definition with no fixed
3771  /// underlying type.

3777  return IntegerType.get<TypeSourceInfo*>()->getType().getUnqualifiedType();
3778  }

3802  /// the rightmost leading 1; that is:
3803  ///
3804  /// MOST NEGATIVE ENUMERATOR PATTERN NUM NEGATIVE BITS
3805  /// ------------------------ ------- -----------------
3806  /// -1 1111111 1

3808  /// -101 1001011 8

3881 /// Represents a struct/union/class. For example:
3882 /// struct X; // Forward declaration, no "body".
3883 /// union Y { int A, B; }; // Has body with members A and B (FieldDecls).
3884 /// This decl will be marked invalid if *any* members are invalid.
3885 class RecordDecl : public TagDecl {
3886  // This class stores some data in DeclContext::RecordDeclBits
3887  // to save some space. Use the provided accessors to access it.
3888 public:
3889  friend class DeclContext;
3890  /// Enum that represents the different ways arguments are passed to and
3891  /// returned from function calls. This takes into account the target-specific
3892  /// and version-specific rules along with the rules determined by the
3893  /// language.
3894  enum ArgPassingKind : unsigned {
3895  /// The argument of this type can be passed directly in registers.
3896  APK_CanPassInRegs,
3897 
3898  /// The argument of this type cannot be passed directly in registers.
3899  /// Records containing this type as a subobject are not forced to be passed
3900  /// indirectly. This value is used only in C++. This value is required by
3901  /// C++ because, in uncommon situations, it is possible for a class to have
3902  /// only trivial copy/move constructors even when one of its subobjects has
3903  /// a non-trivial copy/move constructor (if e.g. the corresponding copy/move
3904  /// constructor in the derived class is deleted).
3905  APK_CannotPassInRegs,
3906 
3907  /// The argument of this type cannot be passed directly in registers.
3908  /// Records containing this type as a subobject are forced to be passed
3909  /// indirectly.
3910  APK_CanNeverPassInRegs
3911  };
3912 
3913 protected:
3914  RecordDecl(Kind DK, TagKind TK, const ASTContext &C, DeclContext *DC,
3915  SourceLocation StartLoc, SourceLocation IdLoc,
3916  IdentifierInfo *Id, RecordDecl *PrevDecl);

3919  static RecordDecl *Create(const ASTContext &C, TagKind TK, DeclContext *DC,
3920  SourceLocation StartLoc, SourceLocation IdLoc,
3921  IdentifierInfo *Id, RecordDecl* PrevDecl = nullptr);

3926  static_cast<TagDecl *>(this)->getPreviousDecl());

3929  return const_cast<RecordDecl*>(this)->getPreviousDecl();
3930  }

3934  }

3936  return const_cast<RecordDecl*>(this)->getMostRecentDecl();

4082  /// Returns the RecordDecl that actually defines
4083  /// this struct/union/class. When determining whether or not a
4084  /// struct/union/class is completely defined, one should use this
4085  /// method as opposed to 'isCompleteDefinition'.
4086  /// 'isCompleteDefinition' indicates whether or not a specific
4087  /// RecordDecl is a completed definition, not whether or not the
4088  /// record type is defined. This method returns NULL if there is
4089  /// no RecordDecl that defines the struct/union/tag.
4090  RecordDecl *getDefinition() const {
4091  return cast_or_null<RecordDecl>(TagDecl::getDefinition());
4092  }

4099  // Iterator access to field members. The field iterator only visits
4100  // the non-static data members of this class, ignoring any static
4101  // data members, functions, constructors, destructors, etc.
4102  using field_iterator = specific_decl_iterator<FieldDecl>;
4103  using field_range = llvm::iterator_range<specific_decl_iterator<FieldDecl>>;
4104 
4105  field_range fields() const { return field_range(field_begin(), field_end()); }
4106  field_iterator field_begin() const;
4107
